The catalytic performance is significantly affected by the specific surface area of the material. Fig. 5
                         shows the N2 adsorption-desorption isotherms of the hybrid films. All curves showed type IV isotherms combined with H3 hysteresis loops, indicating the mesoporous structures of the hybrid films [40]. According to the results of the BET test (Table 1
                        ), PC-TC with a ridge-like morphology exhibited the largest BET specific surface area (SBET) of 24.13 m2 g−1 among all hybrid films. The large specific surface area of the ridge-like PC-TC hybrid film ensures the exposure of more catalytic active sites.

The light absorption abilities of the films were tested by UV–vis diffuse reflectance spectra (UV–vis DRS) (Fig. 6(a)
                        ). The PC-T, P-TC and PC-TC with the introduced CQDs all showed enhancement for visible light absorption compared to P-T. The band gap (Eg) of can be calculated by the Kubelka-Munke formula: ahv = A(hv − Eg)
                           n/2, where a refers to the absorption coefficient, A is a constant, and hv represents the photon energy. The Tauc's plots of the hybrid films are shown in Fig. 6(b). The Eg values of P-T, PC-T, P-TC and PC-TC are 3.15 eV, 3.09 eV, 3.05 eV and 2.91 eV, respectively. The PL results (Fig. 6(c)) indicated that the electron-hole recombination efficiency follows the following order: P-T > PC-T > P-TC > PC-TC. The lowest PL peak intensity of PC-TC implied its lowest photogenerated electron-hole recombination efficiency. The results of the hybrid film EIS test (Fig. 6(d)) were consistent with PL, in which the Nyquist plots of PC-TC also exhibited the smallest electron transport resistance. The superior optical, separation properties, and charge transport of PC-TC can be attributed to: (1) The absorption ability of visible light by the film was strengthened after introduction of CQDs. (2) The Eg of the hybrid material is narrowed due to the chemical and electronic coupling between the conduction band state of TiO2 and the π state of the graphitic intrinsic CQDs [41]. (3) The CQDs embedded within the PVDF film matrix (channel Ⅰ) and TiO2 (channel Ⅱ), as well as the Ti-F coordination bonds (channel Ⅲ) with electron trapping ability, established multiple channels for electron transfer, thus the charge separation was significantly promoted. The resulting regularities of UV–vis DRS and PL also indicated the presence of multiple channels for electron transfer in the hybrid film.

Dynamic piezo-photocatalytic degradation experiments were performed (Fig. 9(a)
                         and (b)). In the dynamic degradation process, the adsorption and catalytic degradation performance of RhB by the hybrid film was significantly enhanced compared to the static photocatalytic process (η reached 95.26 % within 100 min.) (Table S1). This can be ascribed to the fact that (1) the flow exchange of dyes on the catalytic film and the adsorption of RhB were significantly enhanced by the dynamic process (the adsorption of RhB by PC-TC increased from 6.24 % to 31.53 % within 60 min). (2) The catalytic degradation of dyes was accelerated by the piezoelectric catalytic effect of flexible PVDF-based hybrid films under flowing solution conditions. During the dynamic catalysis process, an IEF was established in the S-scheme TiO2@CQDs heterostructure. In addition, the flowing dye solution also led to an IEF in the hybrid film (electrons migrated to the positive piezoelectric potential position, while holes migrated to the negative piezoelectric potential position [46]). As a result, the catalytic degradation of RhB was significantly driven by the dual IEF. The ks value of the dynamic "piezo-photocatalytic" process of the PC-TC reached 0.215 mL min−1 cm−2 (Fig. 9(c)), which is approximately 2.3 times of the static photocatalysis (0.094 mL min−1 cm−2). This result indicated that a dynamic reactor based on PC-TC with piezo-photocatalytic effect could realize efficient removal of pollutants in water by utilizing mechanical energy (flow solution) and solar energy. In addition, the piezo-catalytic performance of the hybrid films was evaluated in the presence of flowing solution only and without light irradiation. The hybrid films exhibited effective degradation for RhB confirming the piezo-catalytic degradation ability of the hybrid films (Fig. 9(d)). The degradation experiments of tetracycline by hybrid films were also carried out. It can be seen from Fig. S4 that the hybrid films also exhibited excellent catalytic degradation performance for tetracycline (the η of PC-TC reached 91.82 % within 100 min). It can be calculated from the thermogravimetric (TG) results (Fig. S5) that the amount of catalyst in the hybrid film is about 0.61 mg. Compared with other types of heterostructures (Table S2) and photocatalytic films (Table 2
                        ) in the literature, the hybrid film with S-scheme heterostructure in this work exhibits excellent η and higher ks with low catalyst dosage and small film area. The effects of the flow rate of dye solution and the CQDs doping on the dynamic piezo-photocatalytic degradation efficiency was investigated. The flow rate of liquid is a critical factor affecting the dynamic degradation of dye by the film reactor. As shown in Fig. 9(e), the η was 92.27 % within 100 min at a flow rate of 8 mL min−1 and gradually increased with increasing flow rate. The η reached 97.36 % when the flow rate increased to 56 mL min−1. This was due to the fact that a larger flow rate increased the pressure exerted by the fluid on the film, which increased the film deformation, improved the charge generation rate and boosted the piezo-photocatalytic process [47]. However, the η decreased to 80.45 % after further increasing the flow rate (152 mL min−1). This was attributed to the high flow rate, which reduced the residence time of the dye on the film surface, inhibited the adsorption and catalytic reactions. The corresponding exerted pressure at different flow rates are shown in Table S3. The effect of CQDs doping in the TBOT precursor solution on the η during the preparation of hybrid films was explored and shown in Fig. 9(f). The η of the hybrid film was firstly enhanced with the increase of CQDs doping concentration. In contrast, the η decreased when the CQDs doping concentration increased to 9 g L−1. This was due to the excessive CQDs in TiO2@CQDs that hinder the light absorption by catalysts and obscure catalytic active sites [48]. The maximum η of PC-TC3 (98.61 %) was achieved at a CQDs doping concentration of 3 g L−1.
